revision.text:
Events in world sport through the years 1766 to 1770.
==Bando== '''Events''' * A game similar to [[bandy]] known in Wales as "[[bando (sport)|bando]]", a term used in a dictionary by John Walters (published 1770 to 1794). Bando was particularly popular in the Cynffig-Margam district of the Vale of Glamorgan where wide stretches of sandy beaches afford ample room for play.<ref name="Davies">{{cite book |last=Davies |first=John |author2=Jenkins, Nigel |title=The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales |year=2008 |publisher=University of Wales Press |location=Cardiff |isbn=978-0-7083-1953-6}}</ref>
==[[Boxing]]== '''Events''' * 21 May 1766 — In his first defence of the title, Juchau lost to Bill Darts at [[Guildford]] after forty minutes and 17 rounds.<ref name=TJ>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/juchau-tom.htm |title=Tom Juchau |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=16 October 2017}}</ref> * April 1767 — Jack Broughton defeated an unnamed opponent in [[Lambeth]] after 15 minutes.<ref name=JB>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/broughton-jack.htm |title=Jack Broughton |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> * July 1767 — Darts defeated a bargeman called Doggett at [[Melksham]] after one hour and six rounds.<ref name=Darts>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/darts-william.htm |title=Bill Darts |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> * 13 October 1767 — Darts defeated a butcher called Swansey at [[Epping Forest]] after fifteen minutes.<ref name=Darts/> * 1769 — Tom Lyons defeated many minor opponents in street fights and in turn-ups in London.<ref name=Lyons>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/lyons-tom.htm |title=Tom Lyons |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> * 1769 — Lyons received challenges from Darts and Peter Corcoran. He declined both and is believed to have retired.<ref name=Lyons/> Darts reclaimed the English title.<ref name=Darts/> * 27 June 1769 — Darts was defeated by Tom Lyons at Kingston-upon-Thames after 45 minutes.<ref name=Darts/> * 4 July 1769 — Bill "The Nailer" Stevens defeated John McGuire in a 20-minute fight at Bloomsbury Fields.<ref name=WS>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/stevens-william.htm |title=Bill Stevens |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref> * August 1769 — Bill Turner defeated Bill "The Nailer" Stevens in a 2-hour 10 minute fight in London.<ref name=WS/> * 4 September 1769 — Peter Corcoran defeated Bill Turner in London after an 11-round 20 minute fight. Some other sources say Bill Turner had won the fight.<ref name=PC>{{cite web |url=http://www.cyberboxingzone.com/boxing/corcoran.htm |title=Peter Corcoran |publisher=Cyber Boxing Zone |accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref> * 25 March 1770 — Darts defeated Stephen "Death" Oliver in [[Putney]] after 27 minutes.<ref name=Darts/> * 1770 — Peter Corcoran defeated Bob ("Bricklayer") Smiler and Tom Dalton in london. The length and round of the fights are unknown. Corcoran also defeated Joe Davis in Moorfields. The length and round of this fight is also unknown as well.<ref name=PC/>
==[[Cricket]]== '''Events''' * c.19 June 1766 — an inter-county match between [[Hampshire county cricket teams|Hampshire]] and [[Sussex county cricket teams|Sussex]] was won by Hampshire; evidence exists that teams raised by the [[Hambledon Club]] were representative of both these counties.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} * 1767 — the earliest known [[century (cricket)|century partnership]] recorded as two [[Hambledon Club|Hambledon]] players score 192 for the first wicket against [[Caterham Cricket Club|Caterham]]; the sources do not name the players but they are believed to have been [[Tom Sueter]] and either [[George Leer]] or [[Edward "Curry" Aburrow]].{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} * 3 June 1768 — death of [[William Bedle]] at his home near [[Dartford]]; he "was formerly accounted the most expert cricket player in England" and is the first great player in cricket's history.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} * 1768 — a newspaper report states that [[John Small (cricketer)|John Small]] "fetched above seven score notches off his own bat" when playing for [[Hampshire county cricket teams|Hampshire]] ''versus'' [[Kent county cricket teams|Kent]] at [[Broadhalfpenny Down]]; although it seems to be his second innings score, it may be his match total and so it is not certain if it is the earliest known first-class [[century (cricket)|century]].{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} * 1769 — first mentions in the sources of two of the greatest bowlers of the 18th century, [[Thomas Brett (cricketer)|Thomas Brett]] and [[Lumpy Stevens]].{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} * 1769 — [[John Minshull]] scored 107 in a minor match and this is the earliest known [[century (cricket)|century]] definitely recorded in any class of cricket.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} * 1769 — [[Tom Sueter]] and [[George Leer]] shared a partnership of 128 for [[Hampshire county cricket teams|Hampshire]] v [[Surrey county cricket teams|Surrey]] at [[Broadhalfpenny Down]], the second known century partnership in cricket's history.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} * 1770 — in the year of the so-called "[[Boston Massacre]]", which occurred on Monday, 5 March, there is a report in the ''Middlesex Journal'' on Thursday, 16 August that: "about three days before the meeting of Parliament, a grand Cricket Match will be played by 11 of the Ministry against 11 of the Patriots, when great sport is expected".<ref>Buckley, p. 53.</ref>
==[[Horse racing]]== '''Events''' * 1770 - [[Eclipse (horse)|Eclipse]] retired undefeated after eighteen races
