[[File:Wally_Moon_1961.png|right|150|thumb|[[Wally Moon]], for whom the term "moonshot" was named]] In baseball, a '''moonshot''' is referred to as a [[home run]] that travels a great distance vertically. The term "Moonshot" was coined by [[MLB Hall of Fame]] former [[Dodgers]] broadcaster [[Vin Scully]], describing high home runs by [[Wally Moon]]. <ref >https:// youtu.be/p7l-As7c5hM</ref > The term would later be referenced in newspapers as "Moon Shots".<ref>http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-moon23mar23,0,4261963.story#axzz2lalysUWD</ref> Moon's home runs at the [[L.A. Coliseum]] gained (perhaps overstated<ref>http://www.hardballtimes.com/moon-shots/</ref>) recognition for being to the [[opposite field]],<ref>http://www.hardballtimes.com/moon-shots/</ref> where the distance of the fence was merely {{convert|251|ft}} from home plate, but towered {{convert|42|ft}} high - for comparison, Fenway Park's famous [[Green Monster]] is {{convert|37|ft}} tall.
<!-- Nearly all of these are based on a misunderstood definition of "moonshot" (perhaps originally used ironically - similar to calling a devastating body check in hockey a "love nudge"), which seems to be solely traced to the single bleacherreport.com article, which - in conjunction with this very article - may be the only source which uses the "long = moon" definition.
==Notable examples== * [[Adam Dunn]] hit a {{convert|535|ft|m|adj=on}} moonshot in center field against [[Jose Lima]] at the [[Great American Ball Park]] on August 8, 2004, the longest one in the stadium's history.<ref>http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1211802-the-longest-moon-shot-home-run-in-the-history-of-each-mlb-stadium/page/13</ref> The home run is a popular highlight on home run reels. * [[Giancarlo Stanton]] hit a {{convert|494|ft|m|adj=on}} tape-measure blast at [[Coors Field]] off of [[Josh Roenicke]] on August 17, 2012. Although not the longest home run hit at Coors Field, it is a very popular baseball highlight and was the longest home run of the 2012 season. It was the longest home run hit since 2009. * [[Jose Canseco]] hit a home run into the 5th deck at the [[SkyDome]] during Game 5 of the [[1989 ALCS]], which many people estimated it to be from {{convert|480|to|540|m}}, but according to Hittrackeronline.com, the baseball would have only traveled {{convert|443|ft}} had it come back to field-level.<ref>http://www.hittrackeronline.com/historic.php?id=1989_13</ref> Nonetheless, the home run is still considered one of the most famous moonshots ever. *[[Albert Pujols]] hit a {{convert|455|ft|m|adj=on}} three run homerun off closer [[Brad Lidge]] on October 17, 2005 at [[Minute Maid Park]]. The ball soared well over the train tracks and ricocheted off the support structures in left field. The [[Houston Astros]] were one out away from securing the pennant victory until this monumental blast. Despite the Cardinals' victory in this game, the Astros would in fact go on to win the pennant that year.<ref>http://www.hittrackeronline.com/historic.php?id=2005_6</ref> *[[C. J. Cron]] hit his first major league home run at [[Rogers Center]] off of [[J.A. Happ]] on May 10, 2014, which traveled an estimated {{convert|468|ft}}.<ref>http://www.hittrackeronline.com/hrdetail.php?id=2014_947</ref> -->
