{{Infobox stadium | stadium_name = Palembang Sport and Convention Center | nickname = ''{{smaller|PSCC}}'' | logo_image = | image = | location = Jalan POM IX, [[Palembang]], [[South Sumatra]], [[Indonesia]] | broke_ground = 1971 | renovated = 2010 | opened = {{start date|2011|10|df=yes}} | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator = | surface = | construction_cost = | architect = | tenants = | former_names = Sport Hall (1971-2010) | seating_capacity = 4,000 | coordinates = {{coord|-2.978235|104.745299|type:landmark_region:ID|display=it}} | publictransit = {{rint|light rail}} {{w|Bumi Sriwijaya LRT station|Bumi Sriwijaya Station}} | pushpin_map = Indonesia_Palembang | pushpin_map_caption = Location in [[Palembang]] }}
'''Palembang Sport and Convention Center''' or simply '''PSCC''' (formerly known as the Sport Hall) is a multi-purpose [[indoor arena]] located in the downtown of [[Palembang]], [[South Sumatra]], [[Indonesia]], in one of the city's well-known business area, Centre Point. Established in 2011 for the [[2011 Southeast Asian Games]], it is praised for its modern and chic design, and its [[volleyball]] field is the best in the nation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.ghiboo.com/pscc-arena-indoor-terbaik-di-tanah-air|title=PSCC the country's best indoor arena|publisher=www.ghiboo.com|date=|accessdate=2013-08-08|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130808154010/http://sport.ghiboo.com/pscc-arena-indoor-terbaik-di-tanah-air|archivedate=2013-08-08|df=}}</ref>
==History== PSCC was built in 1971, and inaugurated by the President [[Soeharto]]. It was built for the National Scholar Games (or POMNAS in Indonesian) in the 80s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.detik.com/travel/read/2011/12/15/114203/1791810/1025/palembang-sport-and-convention-center--pscc--saksi-bisu-sea-games-2011|title=Saksi bisu SEA Games|publisher=www.detik.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-08}}</ref>
Later in October 2010, the government renovated the building massively for the [[2011 Southeast Asian Games]], as [[Palembang]] was chosen as the host city.
In October 2011, the building was established with the new contemporary and modern design. The field and the facilities were also renovated nicely.
Before the [[2011 Southeast Asian Games]], the [[2011 Asian Men's Club Volleyball Championship]] was held in the occasion to welcoming the [[Southeast Asian Games|SEA Games]]. The [[Paykan Tehran]] of [[Iran]] ranked 1 in the final standing, followed by Almaty of [[Kazakhstan]] and Shanghai Tang Dynasty of [[China]].
==See also== * [[List of indoor arenas]] * [[Mata Elang International Stadium]] * [[Istora Senayan]] * [[The BritAma Arena]] * [[DBL Arena, Surabaya|DBL Arena]]
